<div id="review_2057734197" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2057734197" />
    <a title="Erin Clemence" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/16907451-erin-clemence"><img alt="Erin Clemence" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1461798513p2/16907451.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2057734197?book_show_action=true">Jul 14, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Erin Clemence" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Erin Clemence" href="/user/show/16907451-erin-clemence">Erin Clemence</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780062306845" href="/book/show/23215456-the-miniaturist">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2057734197" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17876490066001546901">“The Miniaturist” by Jessie Burton really took me by surprise. This historical fiction novel really pulled me in and left me guessing, with its short chapters and strong, developed characters, this novel was just as addicting as it was delightful. <br/><i> In Amsterdam in 1686, Nella arrives at the doorstep of an illustrious businessman, ready and willing to take on the responsibility of being his wife. As she struggles to fit in, her husband buys her a miniature house (think, dollhouse of sorts) and Ne</i></span>
  <span id="freeText17876490066001546901" style="display:none">“The Miniaturist” by Jessie Burton really took me by surprise. This historical fiction novel really pulled me in and left me guessing, with its short chapters and strong, developed characters, this novel was just as addicting as it was delightful. <br /><i> In Amsterdam in 1686, Nella arrives at the doorstep of an illustrious businessman, ready and willing to take on the responsibility of being his wife. As she struggles to fit in, her husband buys her a miniature house (think, dollhouse of sorts) and Nella sets to work furnishing it. But the miniaturist she hires to construct the houses’ tiny pieces seems to know the secrets of Nella’s household- secrets that even she, Nella, is just discovering. Nella then begins to question the environment around her- how does the miniaturist know so much and how true are the predictions? </i><br />“The Miniaturist” was written creatively and passionately, making it easy to read this novel in its entirety (easily in one sitting). The surprises in Burton’s plot are unexpected and unpredictable, endearing the reader to the storyline even more. The female characters are proud and strong, unwilling to acclimate to the patriarchal society and its expectations. <br />This novel has something for everyone- romance, drama, intrigue, family secrets…even a tiny dollhouse. I enjoyed this book more than I thought I would, and wasn’t prepared for the novels’ gripping and compelling storyline. “The Miniaturist” was a best seller and long-listed for two infamous literary awards, and with good reason. Definitely one of the best historical fiction novels I have read this year, if not ever. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="17876490066001546901" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


